				<p>
				<font face="verdana" size="2"><Blockquote>
<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/029061.html">HUGE Faction Problem (A bug and a half)</a></B><P>

I've already reported this on the bug board, but I'm curious if this is intentional:
After talking to others with faction problems, we have all realized the following:
IF one of your factions is maxed out warmly, when you kill a mob/do a quest that adjusts both this faction and others, nothing will happen. The "Faction circuit" is in series not in parallel.<P>

<B>Call it a stealth fix, to be fair...<P>

Again, we just forgot to mention this in the patch message last time. It will be in this weeks patch message.<P>

Better late than never.<P>

Alan</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/030715.html">Absor are you kidding me?</a></B><P>

SpineDoc wrote: "You closed my thread because you could not hack the flame, ok I can understand that, especially in this environment."<P>

<B>Actually, I closed it because it was your second (third?) post on the same topic AND because you were flaming.<P>

I understand your desire to see these issues fixed. We want them fixed too.<P>

Unfortunately, it's going to have to wait a while longer. Keep the post on the QA board current (and flame free) and when we can, we'll look into it. Right now our testers are very, very busy.<P>

Alan</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

Spinedoc wrote: "Shaddup dude. This has nothing to do with the flame so just keep your trolls to yourself Brainiac."<P>

<B>and</B><P>

"The only thing simple here is you man."<P>

<B>And this, once again, is the reason that I'm closing your thread. I only asked that you not insult people.<P>

Alan</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/034692.html">Why VI should change content: response to Koen42</a></B><P>

Which brings us to VI. It is cost prohibitive for them to constantly update the game to provide a challange. I understand that EQ is not a turn based strategy war game, but why should that make a difference. If EQ was designed to be predominatly PvP, then I would agree that the class balance issues that people talk about should be seriously looked at. But this is a PvE game. Which means that strategy against the AI is most important. Hence, if players find a way to make something challanging easy, then not only should a question of if it should be fixed/changed/nerfed etc. be brought up, players should expect it; and demand it.<P>

<B>An interesting thread. Perhaps a bit over my head, intellectually… <P>

I think it's wrong to imply that you can only do one or the other, either increase the power of the monsters OR decrease the power of player characters, if your goal is to make the game harder (and that's IF…).<P>

The real world answer is that you do both as the situation requires. In the case of one bit of the picture being off, say an item or a spell that makes one class or character type or tactic too powerful, relatively, you obviously reduce the power of that item. If you want to make the world as a whole more difficult for the heroes in it, then you can do either, really. Obviously the preferable method is to increase the AI for the monsters, or find other clever ways to make them more powerful.<P>

That being said, don't go overboard. If we do something that reduces the power of an item or spell or somesuch, it's done in consideration of the whole. I like to picture class balance as a sort of sea (ok, I've never pictured it that way until just now…). Waves are expected, even desirable. But when you see a tsunami, what do you do? Do you raise the ocean or lower the wave? Keep in mind that if you raise the ocean you'll drown the world…<P>

I love bad analogies. :)<P>

Alan</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

PimpyDaddyFroglock wrote: "First, the mass-market condition of EQ violates the postulate that global upward adjustment of difficulty level is necessary. The average player does not have the time or skill to take on these new challenges, and finds the game hard enough as it is."<P>

<B>You're right. But you've also missed a bit of scale as well. Those same people, the 'average' player, will, for the most part, not be involved in these new challenges. The trick is to upscale things where the 'advanced' players will be, i.e. Veeshan's Peak… There is, admittedly, a ripple effect when adjustments for balance are done that does affect all players. But, once again, those things are different than raising the challenge level. Not that it's always easy to tell the two apart…</B><P>

"As it is, many players believe that the global nerfs are being placed there simply to slow the progress against thier already maxed out gaming abilities. This condition alienates and drives away the mainstream players, who are the ones that Verant should care the most about."<P>

<B>Some players do see it that way, and that's unfortunate. But I disagree that it drives away the mainstream players. The mainstream player will rarely even know that such changes were made. If I'm the average player and I don't play a necromancer or I just started playing today, I would never know, or care, that necromancer pets used to stay around no matter how long the necromancer was under a feign death. The mainstream player isn't going to notice those things, or is going to shrug and continue to play.</B><P>

"My points are two: <P>

Adding additional content to satisfy the 20% is nice, but in the EQ world it hurts the mainstream a lot more if that content results in an overall difficulty increase. Just say no to nerfing to make things harder. <P>

It doesn't matter how uber the gear of that 20% is, because the rest of us will never see it. When everyone is nerfed to stop a few, you are doing the wrong thing. Just say no to nerfing to account for new content introduction."<P>

<B>I kind of agree with your first point. But I can't think of any time when we've added content that has made the game as a whole harder for anyone. Given them more challenges (of the optional sort), yes. Made the game itself harder, no. I think you are confusing adding content with balancing the game itself, which really are two different things.<P>

Nerfing to account for new content… I'm interested in an example of that, I can't think of any. Something like that could be good or bad. If the 'nerf' is something that fixes a broken mechanic in the game that was preventing the addition of some new content, then I claim it a good thing, despite the negatives. Poorly added new content that messes something else up would be a bad thing.<P>

Oh, and bump. :)<P>

Alan</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/034932.html">Why do DE Newbie guards SUCK?</a></B><P>

Vanayre wrote: "Im not talking about guards in any other zone but the newbie zones for all other people that will talk about the WC or EC guards."<P>

"b. 2 feeble guards that hit the Young Kodiak for 16 points of damage while the Kodiak happily hits you and mauls you for 20 to 40."<P>

<B>This has already been answered by other posters, but I'll add my voice.<P>

Look at what you are talking about. Newbie guards protect the new characters. In Freeport those are the people that can hunt in the bat yards. In Neriak it's those that hunt in the snake yard. In your second point you talk about the feeble guard not being able to kill Young Kodiaks… And yet, you find opponents of Young Kodiak danger level out in East or West Commons…<P>

Yes, the gate guards are the 'newbie' guards for Nektulos.<P>

And there are other guards that are hunted, take a look out in the Karanas. Head over to Steamfont…<P>

I guess my question to you is, why does in matter that those guards are killed? Humans in Freeport have the same level of guard protection in the area that they fight in at that level. I guess I'm confused by your anger at this situation…<P>

By the way, I agree about the Lavastorm thing. I've hunted there often enough, with absolutely no reason to fight any inkie guards to get there.<P>

Alan</B><P>

